LOOK
====

The look ("lookout") command is a ship's short-range "eyes on deck"
check — very different from radar. It doesn't sweep a wide area of
terrain; it reveals only the 7 hexes immediately around the ship
(itself plus its 6 neighbors, land only — water isn't reported), and
separately reports any *foreign* ships nearby within visual range.
It's the ship counterpart to 'llook' (land units) — see 'info llook'.

COMMAND
-------
  look SHIP-SPEC      Look out from ship(s) matching SHIP-SPEC
  lookout SHIP-SPEC   Same command, long name
  look *              Look out from every owned ship
  look c              Look out from every ship in fleet c

SHIP-SPEC accepts a uid, a uid range, a comma list, "*", "~" (ships
with no fleet assigned), or a single letter naming a fleet.

It's also available inline, mid-route, as the 'l' token in a
'navigate' command — see 'info navigate'.

WHAT IT SHOWS
-------------
  1. The 7-hex patch around the ship (self + 6 neighbors), for any
     non-water tile: "Your <type> N% efficient with N civ with N mil
     @ x,y" for your own sectors, or an approximate (rounded to the
     nearest 10) version for a foreign nation's. This also updates
     your bmap for those tiles.

  2. Any foreign ship within visual range: "Nation #N <shiptype> @
     x,y". Range depends on how far YOUR ship can see (its own
     visual range/tech/efficiency) and how VISIBLE the target is
     (its own type's visibility stat, reduced if it's built well
     above its type's base tech requirement — a stealthier hull).

SUBMARINES
----------
  A submarine sitting at sea is invisible to a plain look — only
  'sonar' can find a submerged sub (see 'info sonar'). Looking FROM a
  submarine also caps your own range to 1 hex, matching how
  submarines trade reach for stealth.

EXAMPLES
--------
  look *          Look out from every owned ship.
  look 5          Look out from ship 5 only.
  look c          Look out from every ship in fleet c.

SEE ALSO
--------
  info llook       The land-unit counterpart
  info sradar      Longer-range terrain sweep, no enemy-unit detail
  info sonar       Active sonar pinging — the only way to find subs
  info navigate    Ship movement, including the inline 'r'/'l'/'s' tokens
  info fleetadd    Group ships so a letter selects the whole fleet
